\section{Identification}{

The target estimand is the cumulative incidence
\verb{P(Y^\{a_Y, a_D, c_bar=0\}_\{K+1\} = 1)} for each of the four arms
\verb{(a_Y, a_D)}. Identification under the separable-effects framework
requires:

\itemize{
\item The \strong{generalized decomposition assumption (GDA)}: the
observed treatment \code{A} decomposes into components \code{A_Y} and \code{A_D}
that could in principle be assigned different values in a future
four-arm trial.
\item Standard causal conditions — \strong{treatment exchangeability}
(E1, holds by design in an RCT), \strong{censoring exchangeability}
(E2, ignorable censoring), \strong{consistency}, and \strong{positivity}.
\item The two \strong{dismissible component conditions} —
\strong{Δ1}: the cause-specific hazard of \code{Y} does not depend on \code{a_D}
given covariate history; and \strong{Δ2}: the cause-specific hazard
of \code{D} does not depend on \code{a_Y} given covariate history.
}

GDA, Δ1, and Δ2 are untestable from observed data — they are causal
/ biological claims, not statistical properties. Run \code{\link[=assumptions]{assumptions()}}
on the fit to inspect the full identification block, including the
two decompositions (A and B) of the total effect. A numeric isolation
read-out (swap-weight ranges) is planned but currently deferred
pending a math check; see \verb{@section Isolation read-out (deferred)}
on \code{\link[=assumptions]{assumptions()}}.
}

\section{Censoring handling}{

Censoring is treated differently by g-formula and IPW:
\itemize{
\item \strong{G-formula} always assumes \strong{independent censoring given the
adjustment covariates}.
\item \strong{IPW} can optionally apply inverse probability of censoring weights
(IPCW) via the \code{ipcw} argument.
}
}

