}

\section{IPW weight columns}{

The IPW pipeline writes the following per-row weight columns onto the
working person-time data (available as \code{fit$weights$pt_data_weighted}
and summarised in \code{diagnostic(fit)$weight_summary}). Subscripts use
\code{j} for interval index and \code{k} for the index of the row.

\describe{
\item{\code{w_cens}}{Inverse probability of remaining uncensored
through interval \code{k}, from the censoring-hazard model \code{C ~ A + L}:
\eqn{w_{cens, k} = 1 / \prod_{j \leq k} P(C_{j+1} = 0 \,|\, \text{history}_j, A, L)}.
Populated only when \code{ipcw = TRUE} and at least one IPW
representation is requested. Used by both IPW Rep 1 and Rep 2.}
\item{\code{w_a}}{Treatment (propensity) weight from the propensity
model \code{A ~ L}. Unstabilized:
\eqn{w_{a} = 1 / P(A = a \,|\, L)}; stabilized (when
\code{formulas$A_num} is provided): the marginal-over-conditional ratio.
Populated whenever any IPW method runs. Used by both Reps.}
\item{\code{w_d_arm_10}, \code{w_d_arm_01}}{D-component swap weights for
Rep 1 (D-swap representation). For arm \verb{(a_Y, a_D)} with
\verb{a_Y \\neq a_D}, Rep 1 stands in \code{A = a_Y} and reweights to
swap the D-cumulative-survival ratio:
\eqn{w_{D, k}^{(a_Y, a_D)} =
      \prod_{j \leq k}
      P(D_{j+1} = 0 \,|\, \text{hist}_j, A = a_D) /
      P(D_{j+1} = 0 \,|\, \text{hist}_j, A = a_Y)}.
\code{arm_10} is \verb{(a_Y = 1, a_D = 0)}; \code{arm_01} is \verb{(a_Y = 0, a_D = 1)}.
\code{NA_real_} on rows whose \code{A} does not equal the stand-in.}
\item{\code{w_y_arm_10}, \code{w_y_arm_01}}{Y-component swap weights for
Rep 2 (Y-swap representation). For arm \verb{(a_Y, a_D)} with
\verb{a_Y \\neq a_D}, Rep 2 stands in \code{A = a_D} and reweights using a
hazard-ratio times lagged-cumulative-survival ratio:
\eqn{w_{Y, k}^{(a_Y, a_D)} =
      \frac{P(Y_{k+1} = 1 \,|\, \text{hist}_k, A = a_Y)}{P(Y_{k+1} = 1 \,|\, \text{hist}_k, A = a_D)}
      \cdot
      \frac{\prod_{j < k} P(Y_{j+1} = 0 \,|\, \text{hist}_j, A = a_Y)}{\prod_{j < k} P(Y_{j+1} = 0 \,|\, \text{hist}_j, A = a_D)}}.
The denominator hazards are floored at \code{sqrt(.Machine$double.eps)}
to avoid \code{Inf}; rescued rows tend to surface as truncated weights
in \code{diagnostic(fit)$flagged_log} (their pre-truncation magnitude
puts them past the \code{truncate} percentile bounds).
\code{NA_real_} on rows whose \code{A} does not equal the stand-in.}
}

All four swap-weight columns and \code{w_cens} / \code{w_a} are subjected to
the symmetric percentile truncation specified by the \code{truncate}
argument (Cole & Hernán 2008 AJE) before they are multiplied into
the per-arm Hajek estimator.
